Make apsw's sdist build safe to cross-compile for iOS / Android.

apsw's PyPI sdist does NOT bundle the SQLite amalgamation. Its bundled
`setup.apsw` config sets `fetch = True`, so the wheel build downloads the
version-matched SQLite amalgamation (sqlite-autoconf-<ver>.tar.gz) from
sqlite.org into a `sqlite3/` directory; `findamalgamation()` then statically
compiles `sqlite3/sqlite3.c` straight into the extension
(APSW_USE_SQLITE_AMALGAMATION=1) -> a self-contained .so with no external
libsqlite3 link. That part is exactly what we want for mobile.

Three default behaviours are host-tainted and must be neutralised for a
cross-compile:

  1. After fetching the amalgamation, setup.py runs `./configure` inside
     sqlite3/ on non-Windows hosts (autosetup), generating sqlite3/sqlite_cfg.h
     which is then consumed via _HAVE_SQLITE_CONFIG_H=1. Under crossenv that
     configure probes/links for the BUILD machine (macOS), not the iOS/Android
     target, baking host feature detection into the wheel. Drop the configure
     run entirely; the SQLite amalgamation compiles fine with its built-in
     defaults plus apsw's own SQLITE_ENABLE_* flags (from enable_all_extensions).

  2. The full-source fetch (`fc.all = True`) pulls sqlite-src + vec1 + sqlar +
     zlib zips from several hosts -- fragile and unnecessary; only the
     amalgamation tarball is needed for findamalgamation(). Set `fc.all = False`
     so just sqlite-autoconf-<ver>.tar.gz is downloaded.

  3. APSW_FORK_CHECKER is compiled in iff the BUILD python has os.fork (always
     true on a macOS build host). It is target-inappropriate for mobile (iOS
     python typically lacks os.fork) and relies on pthread_atfork. Drop the
     define so the mobile wheel matches its target rather than the build host.

